h2.under 1) Write with your eraser
p You get 100 bucks for every word you rub out from your title:
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt1.png" alt="Trello landing page").img__100
h2.under 2) Don't exaggerate
p An honest line always feels warmer:
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt2.jpg" alt="Volkswagon old ads").img__100
h2.under 3) No one cares what you can do
p Everyone cares what you can do!{' '}
  span.italic for them
  | .
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt3.jpg" alt="Apple iPod original ads").img__100
h2.under 4) Avoid the passive voice
p It's indirect and awkward:
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt4.png" alt="Passive voice").img__100
h2.under 5) Don't kill your personality
p The best brands feel “real”:
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt11a.png" alt="Andie's CEO email").img__100
h2.under 6) Avoid “landing page words”
p
  span.italic Unlock
  | ,!{' '}
  span.italic unleash
  | ,!{' '}
  span.italic enhance
  | ,!{' '}
  span.italic exceed
  | ,!{' '}
  span.italic empower
  | ,!{' '}
  span.italic supercharge
  | , etc.
p Real people don't use them.
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt13.png" alt="Frontend mentor copywriting").img__100
h2.under 7) Find the tension
p “Pleasant” gets forgotten. Conflict creates interest:
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt12d.png" alt="Lemonade landing page copywriting").img__100
h2.under 8) Write how you talk
p Casual. Colloquial. Full of pronouns:
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt5.png" alt="Basecamps landing page copywriting").img__100
h2.under 9) Avoid “contained” titles
p Write something that pulls your reader down your page:
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt14.png" alt="Zenbu landing page copywriting").img__100
h2.under 10) Write scannable copy
p Formatting matters:
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt6.png" alt="Everyone scans Frank Kern").img__100
h2.under 11) Stories make you memorable
p I couldn't list The Ten Commandments. I could tell you what happened to Adam and Eve:
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt8.png" alt="Adjective and verb tips").img__100
h2.under 12) More periods, fewer commas.
p Periods mean short sentences. We like short sentences.
p Commas mean long, painful sentences, like this one, which!{' '}
  span.italic New Yorker
  |!{' '}writers think are clever, but real people find torturous, because they wind on and on without actually saying anything.
p h/t!{' '}
  a(href="https://twitter.com/david_perell/status/1250149037837176834" target="_blank") David Perell
h2.under 13) Kill adverbs. Kill adjectives.
p They're flowery. They're vague. They try too hard:
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt9.png" alt="Adjective and verb tips").img__100
h2.under 14) Think slippery slide
p Every line of copy should lead to the next.
p Watch this ad. You won't be able to stop:
.yt
  iframe(width='' height='' src='https://www.youtube.com/embed/eXL2YukS6Sc' frameborder='0' allow='accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture' allowfullscreen='')
h2.under 15) Fence sitters don't buy
p Go to the edge:
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt7.png" alt="Ernest Shackleton copywriting").img__100
h2.under 16) Your first line is crucial
p If people don’t read it, they’re not going to read your second line either.
p Keep it short:
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt10.png" alt="Joe Sugarman copywriting").img__100
h2.under 17) Copywriting is selling
p Don’t romanticize it. The goal isn't to be clever or cute.
p The goal is to inspire action:
img(src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/harrydry/gdmarketing/ctt16.png" alt="Drift copywriting").img__100
